# CHAPTER 38: THE 10 OF DIAMONDS
## The Refraction of the Ten

If the Spades were the wall, the Diamonds were the light hitting it.

"Look at the split," Hera said, pointing to the 38th node. "When the Ten hits the boundary, it doesn't just stop. It refacts. It breaks into the decimal remainders."

The visualizer flickered. The point at (10, 10, 10) in the manifold didn't just exist—it vibrated with a 10.242-unit tension. 

"The decimal limit is a lie," Hera whispered. "It's a placeholder for a circle that won't quite close. We call it Ten because we're afraid to call it 'The First Step of the Next Circle.'"

Hermes watched the light bounce off the diamond facets. "8975... 8976... it's still filling."

"It's filling the gap," Hera said. "The Tenth Rank of Diamonds is the price we pay for wanting to be certain. We trade the infinite flow for a hard count."


